<TITLE> Elderly couple's Gulshan Ave home raided in midnight grab attempt </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, June 10 (bdnews24.com)A group of armed intruders, claiming to be from ATN Bangla TV station, sought to dislodge an octogenarian couple from their decades-old home on the capital's Gulshan Avenue in the small hours of Wednesday morning. The gang raided the home of Abdul Qaiyum, a retired civil servant, at 1:30am and tried to overpower security guards at 69 Gulshan Avenue but faced stiff resistance from neighbours' security men. Police eventually arrested 11 of the attackers. A number of witnesses alleged that police appeared reluctant to take action. Four of the attackers were detained by guards employed by the next-door neighbour, businessman Abdul Awal Mintoo, a former FBCCI president. The other seven were overpowered inside the Qaiyum house compound. At around 5am, bdnews24.com chief crime correspondent Liton Haider watched a frail Qaiyum file a general diary with police. The Qaiyum family sources say a general diary had been registered with the Gulshan police by the ATN Bangla in which it was claimed the house belonged to the TV station. "The attackers came with a huge signboard," said one witness. The board, still propped in the driveway hours later, read: 'ATN Bangla have bought and own this plot 3WS(A)69'. Qaiyum, who began his civil service career in the colonial era, retired as chairman of BIWTA in the Pakistan days and is widely respected among neighbours. "He owned this house for 40 years," said one Gulshan resident who rushed to help the elderly couple, who lived in the house with their daughter. A number of neighbours alleged police complicity in the whole affair. "They were refusing to arrest the 11 already tied up by the guards," alleged one. "And when my son called the OC, the officer was clearly reluctant to respond, pretending he did not know where the place of occurrence could be," the neighbour said. "This is absolutely unacceptable ... how can this happen in the middle of the night? And on Gulshan Avenue?" fumed another neighbour, who saw